<HEADLINE>
<P>
ART MUSEUM UNDERGOES STAFF CHANGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CATHY CURTIS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Newport Harbor Art Museum has named Kimberly Ann Chafin assistant director of 
finance and chief financial officer, the No. 2 administrative post behind 
museum director Michael Botwinick. 
</P>
<P>
 Chafin's appointment, effective Sept. 22, was one of several upper and 
mid-level staff changes announced Friday.Two top staff members left after only 
one year at Newport Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
 Chafin succeeds Ed Prohaska. Hired in July, 1993, Prohaska accepted a job 
during the summer with the Pacific Asia Museum in Pasadena. Chafin, a CPA, was 
formerly with Lance, Soll & Lunghard in Whittier, where she supervised 
independent audits of cities, nonprofit organizations and corporations. 
</P>
<P>
 Another key post not yet filled is that of director of advancement. Louise 
Cummings left the position to become director of development at the AIDS 
Services Foundation of Orange County next month. Cummings joined the museum 
last September, replacing former director of development Margie M. Shackelford. 
</P>
<P>
 Other staff who have been reassigned include Maxine Gaiber, director of 
marketing and public relations. On Oct. 1, Gaiber will assume new duties as 
director of education and publications. A portion of her current job will be 
taken over by Hillary Streichenberger, assistant to the director, who has been 
promoted to public relations/special events coordinator.  
</P>
<P>
 Among other positions filled was that of longtime registrar Betsy Severance. 
Mary Artino, formerly director of collection management services at the Ruth 
Bloom Gallery in Santa Monica, was appointed exhibition coordinator/registrar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
